This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with image patch matching, which is a common task in computer vision. The use of convolutional neural networks and fully-connected neural networks also supports this assumption. 

The paper also involves sparse coding, which is a technique commonly used in machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) for feature extraction and representation. 

The use of neural networks for comparison and evaluation suggests that the paper may also belong to the neural networks (cs.NE) sub-category. 

Finally, the evaluation of the proposed approach using a popular patch dataset suggests that the paper may also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
